    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "10100c1f_a9992c7d",
        "filename": "milo/common/error.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 100,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002080
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-06-09T00:20:57Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "net/http is fairly low level, so it makes sense for that API layer to allow for flexibility.\n\nFrom an API design perspective, the point of passing in the http status code (at least in my mind) is to be able to signal if the redirect is permanent or temporary.  A good abstraction layer will pick good defaults.  Otherwise an API user may be confronted with a choice of \"Should I pass in 302? or 307?\".  Heck, they can pass in 403 and the library will do nothing to stop them.  Removing the choice space reduces cognitive load.\n\nThat being said, I can see a downside of this being a bool.  In practice if the external API surface looks like:\ncommon.RedirectError(\"...\", http.StatusMoved)\n\nIt looks fairly straightforward compared, even compared to\ncommon.RedirectError(\"...\", true)\nWhich requires one extra step to figure out what \"true\" means.",
      "parentUuid": "ea96bee9_345e79e7",
      "revId": "fcba2f921d28caf0bc5c4a342ae96cd463996b98",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
